 tessellation which fills three-dimensional Euclidean space with non-overlapping
 convex uniform polyhedral cells.

Twenty-eight such honeycombs exist:
* the familiar cubic honeycomb and 7 truncations thereof;
* the alternated cubic honeycomb and 4 truncations thereof;
* 10 prismatic forms based on the uniform plane tilings (11 if including the
  cubic honeycomb);
* 5 modifications of some of the above by elongation and/or gyration.

They can be considered the three-dimensional analogue to the uniform tilings of
the plane.
